<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA020694-0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 010758 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
February 6, 1994, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Book Review; Page 6; Book Review Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
300 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
IN BRIEF: NONFICTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ERIKA TAYLOR 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 THE INNER QUARTERS: Marriage and the Lives of Chinese Women in the Sung Period 
by Patricia Buckley Ebrey (University of California Press: $45; 332 pp.) 
History, well-written, can have the excitement and depth of good fiction along 
with the cultural relevance of a documentary.Most of the time, however, we are 
treated to names, dates and wilted retellings of events that resonate with our 
lives about as much as a stranger's gas bill. 
</P>
<P>
 "The Inner Quarters," Patricia Buckley Ebrey's account of the lives of Chinese 
women during the Sung Period (960-1279), has some fascinating sections. But 
other parts manage to suck the lifeblood out of even the most titillating 
subjects, such as adultery and divorce. Some of Ebrey's best work concerns 
husband and wife relations. Since it was common for a man to bring concubines 
into his household, particularly when his wife's physical beauty began to fade, 
jealousy was a real problem. The writing in this section is insightful and 
vibrant. Another strong chapter concerns women and their work making cloth, an 
extremely important aspect of the economy. 
</P>
<P>
 A word of caution: It seems Ebrey is trying to look at Chinese culture during 
the Sung Period without the framework of contemporary Western ideas. For 
example, here are her thoughts on foot-binding: "One test of our ability to 
understand the mentality of Sung China is to set aside these modern readings of 
the symbolism of foot-binding and to try to see how . . . both men and women . 
. . could have seen tiny bound feet as symbols of beauty rather than 
subjection." 
</P>
<P>
 Wait a minute, many feminists might reply. In Sung China beauty was 
subjection. The majority of these women were cripples. One may wish Ebrey would 
look at this integral part of Sung culture a little more closely. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Book Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA020694-0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 010759 </DOCID>
