<HEADLINE>
<P>
PALM LATITUDES: STATE OF MIND; MR. LUCKY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Mark Ehrman 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 You'd think I was God's favorite the way these announcements told me about all 
the prizes I had won. They tended to be low-key affairs; no famous talk-show 
sidekicks waving through the envelope's cellophane window. One even looked 
horrifyingly like a collection agency notice, emblazoned with the words 
"EXTREMELY URGENT." 
</P>
<P>
 "Please call me at your earliest convenience regarding sweepstakes entry 
149277191," the contents read. I didn't recall entering a sweepstakes but I 
called the toll-free number anyway. I must've sounded too suspicious because 
the person at the other end abruptly got rid of me. 
</P>
<P>
 Determined to claim some prize, I erased all traces of cynicism from my voice 
for my next call, to a company that assured me that I was a sure thing to 
receive at least one of five "major awards." The woman told me I was a 
credit-card holder in good standing and thus chosen for this special promotion. 
She asked for an expiration date from one of my credit cards. I gave her a fake 
one. She went to "access her computer." 
</P>
<P>
 "Congratulations, Mr. Ehrman," she trilled. "Let me tell you about some of the 
awards you'll receive": exciting vacations to Florida, Mexico, Las Vegas and 
Lake Tahoe, not to mention a camera and makeup from Bianca of Beverly Hills. 
Yessiree, more than $2,000 worth of stuff. "Oh, Mr. Ehrman, there's one more 
thing." Seems they needed a "processing fee" up front -- $698.50 to be exact. 
</P>
<P>
 "I don't have it," I pleaded. "I'm broke from Christmas shopping." 
</P>
<P>
 "No problem," she urged. "We'll take it in three payments on your MasterCard." 
I got off the phone.  
</P>
<P>
 "It is in violation of California law for anyone to tell you that you've won a 
prize and then ask you to pay anything," says Herschel Elkins, head of the 
consumer law section of the state attorney general's office. "And that means 
anything -- to buy a product, pay taxes or submit a processing fee." 
</P>
<P>
 Though authorities frequently arrest the perpetrators of these schemes, new 
cons spring up as quickly as the old ones are busted. Indeed, the next day I 
received a card from an outfit in Tampa saying I was "selected to receive a 9 
day/8 night Tropical Vacation Offer." Hotels, beaches, cruises, Disney World -- 
the works. 
</P>
<P>
 As it turns out, there was just one catch . . . . Mark Ehrman 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA020694-0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 010767 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
February 6, 1994, Sunday, Home Edition Correction Appended 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Book Review; Page 9; Book Review Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1367 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
DEEP POCKETS; THE COST OF TALENT: HOW EXECUTIVES AND PROFESSIONALS ARE PAID AND 
HOW IT AFFECTS AMERICA, BY DEREK BOK (FREE PRESS: $22.95; 341 PP.)  
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Allan Sloan, Allan Sloan, a syndicated columnist for Newsday, frequently 
writes about financial excesses. His column appears in the Times' business 
section on Sundays. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Stories about the obscene incomes of top business executives have become one 
of our signs of spring. As the snows melt and robins reappear, corporations 
disclose how much they paid their top executives in the previous year, and how 
much these folks made by exercising their stock options. 
</P>
<P>
 Public outrage has grown in recent years as companies have engaged in massive 
layoffs while the income of top executives has gone to the moon, thanks to 
increases in their salaries and bonuses and -- much more important -- thanks to 
huge profits created by the long-running bull market for stocks. 
</P>
<P>
 Who can forget the late Steve Ross, chairman of Time Warner Inc., knocking 
down $78 million while the company was laying off writers to save money? Who 
can forget General Motors increasing its former chairman's pension 
retroactively while asking the United Auto Workers union to moderate its wage 
and benefit demands? 
</P>
<P>
 Or, for that matter, who can forget last year's announcement that Walt Disney 
Chairman Steven Eisner was taking $200 million in stock-option profits? 
</P>
<P>
 All the uproar has moved executive pay to the front pages from the business 
pages, and fat-cat chief executive officers have become a populist villain. 
Candidate Bill Clinton announced that if elected President, he would introduce 
legislation to stop companies from deducting more than $1 million a year in 
salary and bonuses to top officers. 
</P>
<P>
 Clinton was elected, his proposal became law. The problem is that it's having 
little effect. Companies can still deduct the full expense of non-officers, so 
the Dodgers deduct all of Darryl Strawberry's $4-million-plus annual salary and 
Salomon Brothers can deduct the $5 million it might pay some bond wizard. And, 
provided they go through the proper paper-shuffling, corporations can still 
deduct in full the salaries and bonuses of top executives. 
</P>
<P>
 This is an example of good intentions colliding with real life. It's easy to 
talk a solution, it's much harder to create one that actually works. 
</P>
<P>
 And what does excessive income mean? Compared to what? Most of the huge 
incomes of top executives aren't salaries and bonuses but, rather, profits 
they've made on stock options. The salary income and stock-based income are 
generally lumped together, but they're really separate. Salaries are pretty 
much guaranteed and come from corporate coffers. Stock market profits are a 
whole other game. 
</P>
<P>
 Eisner's $200 million came from options, as did $75 million of Steve Ross' $78 
million. Who's to say they don't deserve the money? Disney's stock market value 
had risen $20 billion during Eisner's regime -- is giving him 1% of the swag so 
unreasonable? And Steve Ross, who did have salaries and perks that I considered 
obscene, made billions of dollars for Warner Communications stockholders when 
he peddled Warner to Time Inc., now Time Warner. Is the $75 million 
unreasonable, considering the billions that Warner shareholders made? 
</P>
<P>
 So even though it's lots of fun to scream about financial excesses -- I do 
that for a living -- it's much easier to scream than it is to solve the problem 
of excessive executive pay. If it's in fact a problem. 
</P>
<P>
 Which brings us to "The Cost of Talent," a book on a populist subject by Derek 
Bok, former president of Harvard University, one of the nation's most elite 
institutions. 
</P>
<P>
 You would hope that such a man would produce an interesting and incisive book 
on such an interesting topic. Unfortunately, you would be wrong. 
</P>
<P>
 The trouble starts on the first page of Chapter 1. Bok, trying to get off to a 
lively start -- that's what we writers are supposed to do -- reconstructs a 
conversation between the chairman of CBS Inc. and anchorman Dan Rather. 
</P>
<P>
 But the writing is a little clunky. Even worse, as Bok honorably and clearly 
discloses in the footnotes, his account is based entirely on other peoples' 
work: a New York Times article and Ken Auletta's 1991 book, "Three Blind Mice." 
</P>
<P>
 To top things off, Bok gets the first name of CBS' chairman wrong. It's 
Laurence Tisch, not Leonard Tisch. If Tisch had given as many millions to 
Harvard as he's given to his alma mater, New York University, which is 
considerably less upscale, Bok or his assistants or his editors would probably 
have gotten the name right. 
</P>
<P>
 While one wrong name isn't that big a deal, getting the name of one of the 
country's most prominent businesspeople wrong on Page 1 is off-putting. And the 
opening anecdote symbolizes what's wrong with this book. 
</P>
<P>
 The book isn't based on original research, or on information gained by 
interviewing the people Bok is writing about. Read all 548 footnotes, and you 
find five based on a random survey of Phi Beta Kappas that Bok did from 
1970-1990, and two more based on numbers that people computed for him. The 
other 541 are all other peoples' work. There's not one footnote based on author 
interviews. Not a good sign. 
</P>
<P>
 Bok, who has spent his life in academe, surveys the literature, comes down 
from his ivory tower and takes us through a convoluted exercise designed to 
show us how Bok concluded the obvious: that many top corporate executives, 
doctors and lawyers are overpaid by any rational standard. What a shocker! He 
decides -- another surprise -- that university professors and schoolteachers 
are underpaid compared to these groups. And that federal civil servants are, 
too. 
</P>
<P>
 Bok says, quite rightly, that the so-called free market doesn't do an 
appropriate job of deciding what to pay the "overpaid" professions, because the 
market isn't really free. Top executives sit on each others' board of directors 
and help decide each others' pay -- which isn't conducive to arm's-length 
bargaining. And very few consumers are in a position to comparison-shop for 
medical and legal services. You don't get doctors' bids on the operating table. 
</P>
<P>
 Fair enough. 
</P>
<P>
 What Bok doesn't stress sufficiently is that his three "underpaid" groups have 
something the "overpaid" groups don't: tenure. Once educators and civil 
servants have been around a while, they're employed for life, provided their 
employer stays in business. Being employed for life is very valuable, even 
though it doesn't show up in your paycheck. Nor does Bok give much weight to 
the fact that doctors and lawyers -- and yes, even chief executives -- 
generally work far longer hours than educators and civil servants. 
</P>
<P>
 Bok is, of course, quite right that many executive incomes have no reasonable 
relationship to how well executives have led their companies. What to do about 
this problem? Bok proposes a sharp increase in tax rates on very high incomes 
to tax away most of the obscene salaries and stock profits earned by overpaid 
executives. But the rich and powerful will find a way to dodge these taxes. And 
even if they don't, taxing ultra-high incomes at ultra-high rates doesn't solve 
the very real morale and fairness problems of paying a chief executive 1,000 
times what a low-ranking employee earns. 
</P>
<P>
 And Bok ignores the problems of private companies, where the really big money 
is earned. Last year, for instance, superstar money-manager George Soros 
reportedly made more than $625 million as his cut of the profits on the money 
he managed for his investors. Soros made Michael Eisner's $200 million, earned 
for Disney options Eisner held for 10 years, look like pocket change. 
</P>
<P>
 Bok talks about expanding educational opportunities -- which is heading in the 
right direction, but not far enough. As long as we're in Ivory Towerland -- Bok 
proposes to equalize opportunities by having the federal government help some 
parents pay for private college, more than a little self-serving for a Harvard 
man -- why not expand economic opportunities? 
</P>
<P>
 Instead of carping about what the No. 1 guy gets, let's encourage -- nay, 
require -- companies to give long-term employees options and bonuses tied to 
the chief executive's package. That would give everyone a piece of the action. 
And it would force boards of directors to think twice before giving away the 
store to the chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
 We also should require Bok to get a little real-world experience before 
telling the rest of us how to run our lives. If he's good, we'll let him 
re-apply for admission for the spring semester. 
</P>
</TEXT>
