<HEADLINE>
<P>
POP EYE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 AND ONE MORE THING: In case you were wondering about the haunting instrumental 
bit of "Blue Moon" used in Norwegian Cruise Lines' current TV ad -- you might 
have seen it during the Super Bowl telecast last week -- it's not the Cowboy 
Junkies. 
</P>
<P>
 Junkies guitarist Michael Timmins says that the group was asked to provide its 
version of the song, which is on the group's 1987 breakthrough album "The 
Trinity Session," for the spot, but declined. 
</P>
<P>
 "I don't have anything against people who let their music be used in 
commercials," he says. "But when it's something we put a lot of heart into, we 
want the audience to feel the same way and I'm not sure they do when it's used 
to sell something." 
</P>
<P>
 As for the version in the ad, Timmins says, "It's flattering that they wanted 
it to sound like us." But he jokingly says he can tell the difference: "I know 
it's not us because this version is played in rhythm."* 
</P>
</TEXT>
