<HEADLINE>
<P>
RECHARGING THE ELECTRIC IDEA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The decision by a number of populous states to follow California's lead in 
fostering development of electric cars gives the Clinton Administration added 
political muscle to prod U.S. auto makers to finally get serious about electric 
vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
 Last week's vote by the Ozone Transport Commission, which represents 12 
Eastern states and the District of Columbia, makes it clear that California -- 
the home of strict emissions rules and the beginnings of an EV industry -- is 
no longer a voice in the wilderness when it comes to promoting EV technology. 
</P>
<P>
 Despite objections from the auto industry, the commission approved a series of 
recommendations that are close to ones already adopted by California. The 
commission recommends that its member states implement a low-emissions program 
beginning in 1996 and require the sale of cleaner cars and light trucks 
starting in 1999. The body also called for a progressive reduction in emissions 
with each model year, beginning in 1999, with a reduction of nearly 50% by 
2003; electric vehicles would meet low- or zero-emissions standards. With its 
vote, the commission formally calls on the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency 
to require "progressively cleaner standards" for automobile emissions. The EPA 
now has nine months to draft final rules on low-emission vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
 The EPA -- and the Administration generally -- has been on the defensive 
lately with regard to clean-air rules and the potential of EV technology. The 
auto industry has mounted a strong lobbying campaign against California's 
strict emissions standards at a time when the Administration has launched a 
"partnership" with Detroit to develop cleaner vehicles (although not 
necessarily electric cars). The states represented on the commission, together 
with California, are home to slightly more than 50% of the nation's population. 
Obviously Detroit knows there is a big potential market for electric vehicles 
in these states, and that it had better get with the program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
