<HEADLINE>
<P>
CITY ARTS: FEAST FOR THE EYES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ERIN J. AUBRY and KIM PAYTON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 By sheer scope, the Artists' Salute to Black History Month qualifies as one of 
the city's biggest annual events recognizing the contributions of African 
Americans. 
</P>
<P>
 Works by more than 150 black painters, sculptors and other visual artists from 
22 states -- the largest exhibit of African American art in the country -- have 
filled both levels of the Baldwin Hills Crenshaw Plaza for the better part of a 
week.Besides the wealth of visual art on display, the salute boasts a schedule 
of special exhibit-related events. 
</P>
<P>
 This year's salute, titled "Our Children . . . Our Hope," includes a parade 
and ceremony at 11 a.m. today for elementary school children who have shown 
exceptional effort in their artwork. 
</P>
<P>
 Other events today, which conclude the salute, are an 11 a.m. forum with 
poster artist Sylvia Walker; a 1 p.m. forum with artists Tina Allen, Varnette 
Honeywood and Cheryl A. Moody, and a 4 p.m. forum with artists Michael Brown, 
Charles Dickson and Paul Goodnight. The exhibit closes at 6 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 Among other Black History Month events in Central Los Angeles this month: 
</P>
<P>
 * "Sweetwater Blues," a musical exploration of African American blues and jazz 
artists; 4 p.m. today; The Theatre of Arts, 4128 Wilshire Blvd.; (213) 883-1508 
($15). 
</P>
<P>
 * The LALA Festival, celebrating the cultural heritage of Louisianians; 
entertainment, food, arts and crafts; 9 a.m. parade from 60th Street and 
Crenshaw Boulevard to Leimert Park; 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. today; (213) 485-2437 
(free). ERIN J. AUBRY and KIM PAYTON 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA020694-0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 011109 </DOCID>
