<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: SOUTH: SOUTH-CENTRAL; CHARGES FILED OVER SPILLED CAR OIL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SANDRA HERNANDEZ 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The city attorney's office has filed criminal charges against a South-Central 
man accused of illegally dumping oil and waste matter. 
</P>
<P>
 Luis Castro, 26, is accused of flushing automobile fluid down a storm drain 
after transmission fluid spilled while he was working on a car in Wilmington, 
according to the city attorney's office. 
</P>
<P>
 Castro, who was to be arraigned Tuesday, failed to appear in Los Angeles 
Municipal Court. If convicted, he faces up to six months in jail or a $1,000 
fine for illegally dumping oil and up to one year in jail and/or a $10,000 fine 
for dumping a hazardous substance on a public street. 
</P>
<P>
 "He was in the middle of working on the car when a police officer from the 
city saw a streak of red transmission fluid, and they interviewed him and he 
didn't realize it was against the law," said Vincent Sato, the deputy city 
attorney handling the case. "It's a problem because once it hits the storm 
drain, it goes straight to Santa Monica Bay or the harbor. That's why we're 
trying to regulate this type of activity." SANDRA HERNANDEZ 
</P>
</TEXT>
